WEBVTT

00:05.964 --> 00:06.881
DOUG MATTHEWS:
We didn't know how

00:06.964 --> 00:08.923
the McDonald's Monopoly game
was fixed.

00:09.130 --> 00:10.673
So, inside the wire room,

00:10.756 --> 00:12.589
people'd sit in there,
getting ready to listen.

00:13.005 --> 00:14.255
And nothing happens.

00:14.339 --> 00:15.673
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

00:15.756 --> 00:19.089
The FBI, we start coming up
with how do we get past winners

00:19.172 --> 00:22.130
to recount how
they allegedly won these pieces.

00:22.756 --> 00:25.381
Locking them into a story
on camera,

00:25.464 --> 00:29.005
takes a B-minus case
and makes it a A-plus case.

00:29.506 --> 00:32.214
For a while, the question was,
"Who is Uncle Jerry?"

00:32.297 --> 00:34.214
We were looking
into Jerry Jacobson.

00:34.506 --> 00:36.756
We thought this may be
the main guy.

00:37.089 --> 00:40.005
But there was always
this inference that Uncle Jerry

00:40.089 --> 00:42.297
somehow connected
to organized crime.

00:42.381 --> 00:45.005
We found out that there was
another Jerry involved,

00:45.089 --> 00:46.589
named Jerry Colombo.

00:47.506 --> 00:50.339
My husband. He was part
of the Colombo crime family.

00:50.422 --> 00:54.422
My Jerry and Jerry Jacobson
became partners

00:54.506 --> 00:57.464
on the Monopoly thing.
My husband picked the winners.

00:57.756 --> 01:00.255
INTERVIEWER:

01:00.631 --> 01:02.923
"Uncle Jerry"
is Jerome Jacobson.

01:03.297 --> 01:06.047
My husband. He got a lot
of my family members involved.

01:06.130 --> 01:07.047
And that isn't all.

01:07.255 --> 01:09.172
That was just a little piece
of the pie.

01:12.005 --> 01:14.130
[bright tone]

01:31.130 --> 01:32.005
- Whiskey.

01:32.089 --> 01:33.589
Where's Oliver?

01:33.673 --> 01:35.714
[cat meows]

01:35.798 --> 01:38.005
Oliver, come on!

01:43.839 --> 01:45.923
I helped pick the winners.

01:46.005 --> 01:49.631
I gave some tickets
to some friends of mine

01:49.714 --> 01:52.798
and family members
who needed it.

01:56.589 --> 02:00.673
I wanted them happy, so...

02:01.631 --> 02:03.422
I gave 'em things.

02:03.506 --> 02:05.839
I was gonna get
the $1 million,

02:05.923 --> 02:07.839
but I gave it to my father.

02:07.923 --> 02:09.798
And, um...

02:11.464 --> 02:16.214
Maybe if certain things
never happened...

02:17.798 --> 02:21.047
This Monopoly thing
would still be going on today.

02:22.422 --> 02:24.464
It's true.

02:24.547 --> 02:27.464
[dramatic music]

02:27.547 --> 02:34.673
♪ ♪

03:34.255 --> 03:35.923
- With Shamrock Productions

03:36.005 --> 03:38.047
and the "Reunion of Winners,"

03:38.130 --> 03:39.964
I think some of them
are pretty legendary,

03:40.047 --> 03:43.673
in terms of
what was captured on film.

03:45.798 --> 03:49.089
- Like Buddy Fisher
and Mr. Hoover,

03:49.172 --> 03:53.297
Gloria Brown was
an instant $1 million winner.

03:53.381 --> 03:57.005
She had won in South Carolina.

03:59.839 --> 04:01.756
- Gloria had said her address

04:01.839 --> 04:05.214
was in the Hilton Head
area of South Carolina,

04:05.297 --> 04:08.464
but she was from
Jacksonville, Florida.

04:09.464 --> 04:10.798
There was always something

04:10.881 --> 04:12.923
that I was trying
to drive out.

04:13.005 --> 04:15.339
I was trying to expand the BS

04:15.422 --> 04:17.339
that they were trying
to put out there

04:17.422 --> 04:20.089
because I know AUSA Devereaux

04:20.172 --> 04:23.255
needs a ground ball,
boy needs something easy.

04:23.339 --> 04:24.673
- [laughs]

04:24.756 --> 04:26.839
- I'm kidding,
he's good at his job.

04:28.881 --> 04:31.089
- It's been a decade,
but I enjoyed it.

04:31.172 --> 04:33.381
First time, yeah...

04:36.506 --> 04:38.381
- Well, I was unemployed
at that time, right in--

04:38.464 --> 04:40.089
- Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

04:40.172 --> 04:42.130
- But I am a social worker.

04:42.214 --> 04:44.923
I just was
taking a break from...

04:45.005 --> 04:46.130
stress.

04:46.214 --> 04:47.881
I'm not doing it anymore,
thank God.

04:47.964 --> 04:49.547
[laughter]

04:50.589 --> 04:52.673
- Yeah. Yeah.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

04:54.130 --> 04:55.089
- No, most--

04:55.172 --> 04:56.756
- Most of my family
is here.

04:56.839 --> 05:00.130
I had a friend, a personal
friend and another friend,

05:00.214 --> 05:02.130
a couple of friends
there that--

05:02.214 --> 05:04.756
basically what I was doing
was a lot of visiting,

05:04.839 --> 05:06.631
job searching at that time,

05:06.714 --> 05:08.589
so, you know,
trying to relocate.

05:08.673 --> 05:11.839
- One thing that struck me
was that Ms. Brown

05:11.923 --> 05:14.005
wasn't as open and friendly

05:14.089 --> 05:17.464
as Mr. Hoover was.

05:17.547 --> 05:20.756
She seemed to be on guard,

05:20.839 --> 05:25.881
whether or not she suspected
something was awry or not,

05:25.964 --> 05:30.172
she just...she just
wasn't as forthcoming.

05:40.589 --> 05:42.089
- Yeah, yeah.

05:44.255 --> 05:45.339
- Yes, yeah.

05:45.422 --> 05:47.130
- Well, in Hilton Head,
you know,

05:47.214 --> 05:49.506
um, during that time I was,
you know, living with a friend,

05:49.589 --> 05:52.798
of course, and, um,
trying to job hunt

05:52.881 --> 05:56.798
and right now,
I have my own agenda,

05:56.881 --> 05:59.839
you know, I have
my patients to care for.

05:59.923 --> 06:02.381
Um...I'm busy, like today

06:02.464 --> 06:04.756
I'm taking a trip, you know,

06:04.839 --> 06:06.339
and, um...

06:06.422 --> 06:08.589
um day-to-day--
I work seven days a week,

06:08.673 --> 06:10.923
basically, you know,
I'm on call all the time.

06:11.005 --> 06:15.297
So compared to back then,
um, and to now,

06:15.381 --> 06:18.005
I would say that, um...

06:18.089 --> 06:21.005
McDonald's have made it so that

06:21.089 --> 06:25.589
I can just lie without
any stress, you know?

06:27.089 --> 06:29.547
- Um, a little over a year,
back and forth.

06:29.631 --> 06:32.839
- Many of the winners were
saying they lived in one area,

06:32.923 --> 06:34.547
but then had a post office box

06:34.631 --> 06:37.214
where they would have
their winnings sent to,

06:37.297 --> 06:39.339
so they would
set up fake addresses.

06:39.422 --> 06:41.881
And so, a lot of the evidence
that I was gathering

06:41.964 --> 06:44.255
was around where they lived,

06:44.339 --> 06:46.381
exactly what store they won

06:46.464 --> 06:49.005
the McDonald's
Monopoly piece at.

06:52.464 --> 06:54.923
- So, I said,
"Gloria, do you remember

06:55.005 --> 06:56.673
the McDonald's where you
went to claim the prize?"

06:56.756 --> 06:58.047
"Absolutely."

06:58.130 --> 06:59.881
"This is a picture."
We took a picture of it

06:59.964 --> 07:02.798
and put it on this board
and she said, "Oh, my God,

07:02.881 --> 07:06.381
that's exactly the one,"
and I said, "You know what,

07:06.464 --> 07:08.881
can you autograph that for us?"

07:11.798 --> 07:12.964
- "Thanks a million."

07:15.673 --> 07:16.839
- [laughing]

07:18.089 --> 07:19.589
- That picture
that she signed,

07:19.673 --> 07:22.589
it was not in Hilton Head,
South Carolina.

07:22.673 --> 07:24.547
It was Jacksonville, Florida.

07:30.756 --> 07:32.297
- No, I sure don't.

07:32.381 --> 07:36.005
- The fake address
was a part of the scheme.

07:36.089 --> 07:38.089
And so, Rick had this
surveillance photo

07:38.172 --> 07:41.089
of a McDonald's
right there in Jacksonville.

07:41.172 --> 07:44.506
And I go, "Oh, my God,
that's perfect."

07:44.589 --> 07:46.547
So I take it with me.
"What are you gonna do?"

07:46.631 --> 07:48.047
And I said, "I'm gonna--
I'm gonna use it.

07:48.130 --> 07:50.172
Wait and see.
I'm gonna show you."

07:52.881 --> 07:56.005
And, as she's doing it, Amy,

07:56.089 --> 07:59.255
she's like,
"Oh, my God, that's just--

07:59.339 --> 08:01.255
that's not it.
That's not it."

08:01.339 --> 08:03.798
And I'm looking over--
it's starting to get louder,

08:03.881 --> 08:07.130
and I'm like, I'm looking back,

08:07.214 --> 08:08.964
"Do you want that here?

08:09.047 --> 08:11.381
I mean--they almost
can hear that."

08:12.464 --> 08:13.923
- Mm-hmm.
- [indistinct speech]

08:14.005 --> 08:15.422
- That's what I love.
[indistinct speech]

08:15.506 --> 08:16.547
Every time I talked to them,

08:16.631 --> 08:18.714
they would just lie, lie, lie.

08:18.798 --> 08:21.589
And it was perfect for
the FBI because it was really

08:21.673 --> 08:24.047
building evidence and helping
them build their case.

08:24.130 --> 08:25.506
But we also wanted to make sure

08:25.589 --> 08:27.130
that it seemed like
we were having fun.

08:27.214 --> 08:28.673
Because, once again,

08:28.756 --> 08:31.089
that's how it would be
at a real shoot.

08:43.714 --> 08:45.214
- Okay.
- Oh, wait--oh, there's--

08:45.297 --> 08:46.839
- Uh, Doug brought
a lot of that energy.

08:46.923 --> 08:48.714
- Up there?
Okay.

08:49.673 --> 08:50.881
- Okay.
[laughter]

08:54.005 --> 08:55.255
- Okay.
Okay.

08:55.339 --> 08:56.714
- Okay.

08:58.339 --> 09:00.339
- That's typical Mathews.
That's what he would do.

09:00.422 --> 09:02.297
- Thanks a million, McDonald's.
[laughs]

09:02.381 --> 09:03.547
- Okay, look right
in the camera

09:03.631 --> 09:04.839
and say it right there.

09:04.923 --> 09:06.673
- Thanks a million,
McDonald's.

09:06.756 --> 09:08.798
- And it was hard sometimes
to keep a straight face,

09:08.881 --> 09:10.381
to be honest with you.

09:10.464 --> 09:12.714
It was very hard at times,
'cause the things we were

09:12.798 --> 09:16.381
doing with the light meter
or the camera and sitting them

09:16.464 --> 09:19.047
and fixing them up,
we had no idea.

09:19.130 --> 09:21.464
- I got my McDonald's
millions--million

09:21.547 --> 09:24.255
at Hilton Head
in South Carolina,

09:24.339 --> 09:26.798
and it made me a...

09:28.547 --> 09:30.005
Millionaire.

09:30.089 --> 09:31.964
- [laughing]
That's cute.

09:32.964 --> 09:34.464
- Pretty close, okay.

09:34.547 --> 09:37.047
- What I figured out
at an early age in the bureau

09:37.130 --> 09:40.964
is, you push it and then you
think it's--you keep pushing.

09:41.047 --> 09:43.381
You never know when
you're gonna hit a wall.

09:43.464 --> 09:45.214
And, of course,
I never found the bottom.

09:45.297 --> 09:47.005
The bottomless
tea glass, right?

09:47.089 --> 09:49.464
It's perfect for me.
Just keep going.

09:49.547 --> 09:51.756
And, of course, she did.

09:51.839 --> 09:53.381
- Ron and I will s--

09:53.464 --> 09:54.673
Ron--
Ugh.

09:58.172 --> 10:00.756
- Ron and I will
see you in Vegas.

10:00.839 --> 10:02.506
Thank you, McDonald's.

10:06.881 --> 10:09.005
[laughter]

10:10.381 --> 10:12.255
- We knew it was
such good evidence

10:12.339 --> 10:14.422
having Gloria sitting here,

10:14.506 --> 10:16.089
just making the story up.

10:16.172 --> 10:19.255
And doing it with this
sincerity--this fake sincerity.

10:19.339 --> 10:21.798
It was--it was--as
a criminal investigator,

10:21.881 --> 10:23.839
it was an awesome
thing to behold.

10:24.673 --> 10:27.673
- There were so many different
layers of the conspiracy

10:27.756 --> 10:29.798
that we were investigating,

10:29.881 --> 10:33.089
and the more
sophisticated a scheme,

10:33.172 --> 10:36.923
the more difficult it is
to prosecute the case.

10:37.005 --> 10:38.714
Now you have actual
video production

10:38.798 --> 10:40.547
that you can show a jury.

10:40.631 --> 10:42.339
That's very powerful.

10:42.422 --> 10:45.172
[upbeat music]

10:45.255 --> 10:49.130
- By this time, literally
almost the whole office now,

10:49.214 --> 10:52.964
or a big majority of them,
have been diverted to work on

10:53.047 --> 10:54.839
what we call
Operation Final Answer.

10:54.923 --> 10:57.798
♪ ♪

10:57.881 --> 11:01.005
- We worked seven days a week
on a regular basis,

11:01.089 --> 11:03.297
but at times it did not
feel like work.

11:03.381 --> 11:06.422
We had great camaraderie
between all of the agents

11:06.506 --> 11:08.547
that were working it,
and we knew the mission is--

11:08.631 --> 11:10.255
what we were
trying to accomplish

11:10.339 --> 11:11.798
was a noble one and a good one.

11:11.881 --> 11:14.297
Um, so nobody ever
complained about it.

11:14.381 --> 11:17.714
♪ ♪

11:17.798 --> 11:20.381
- Things were moving fast,
and naturally,

11:20.464 --> 11:23.172
we always want
to move at our pace.

11:23.255 --> 11:25.756
We wanna control
the timing of things,

11:25.839 --> 11:28.255
and we did not
have that luxury.

11:28.339 --> 11:30.172
The game was running.
There was clock running

11:30.255 --> 11:32.547
on how long we could
keep it a secret.

11:33.339 --> 11:35.839
Throughout this,
we were really, really

11:35.923 --> 11:37.839
racking up incredible evidence,

11:37.923 --> 11:40.714
discovering new people,
proving all different elements

11:40.798 --> 11:43.506
of what was going on.
And we kind of knew

11:43.589 --> 11:45.172
the process of
how these were placed,

11:45.255 --> 11:47.464
but the one thing
that was still out there

11:47.547 --> 11:50.923
was how is Jerry Jacobson
doing this?

11:51.005 --> 11:53.673
That was kind of this nagging,

11:53.756 --> 11:56.381
you know,
this nagging question mark.

11:56.464 --> 11:58.381
- What we had to vet out
here is, who--

11:58.464 --> 12:00.297
who was helping Jerry?

12:03.297 --> 12:05.964
- Hilda Bennett was
the CPA that would travel

12:06.047 --> 12:10.506
with Mr. Jacobson to these
various manufacturing plants.

12:10.589 --> 12:14.798
And we didn't know,
are they in cahoots?

12:15.964 --> 12:17.255
On an investigation,

12:17.339 --> 12:19.005
you just don't
cut somebody out.

12:19.089 --> 12:23.089
And so, we had to surveil
Ms. Bennett as well.

12:32.130 --> 12:35.047
- You want cheese?
- Yep.

12:35.130 --> 12:38.923
- I need to get
a large coffee

12:39.005 --> 12:42.589
with ten cream and five sugar.

12:42.673 --> 12:44.422
- Anything else?

12:44.506 --> 12:46.297
- Yep, another large coffee

12:46.381 --> 12:48.506
with ten cream and five Equal.

12:48.589 --> 12:49.589
- Okay.

12:49.673 --> 12:50.923
- That is Equal?
- Yep.

12:51.005 --> 12:52.381
- Awesome, thank you.
- You're welcome.

12:52.464 --> 12:55.005
- Have a great day.
- Thank you.

12:56.506 --> 12:58.673
- Oh, that's perfect.

13:00.297 --> 13:03.506
The one time I've seen
Uncle Jerry was up in Georgia.

13:03.589 --> 13:05.881
My brother went to go visit.

13:05.964 --> 13:07.714
I stayed in the car.

13:07.798 --> 13:10.422
I didn't get out of the car
because he didn't directly

13:10.506 --> 13:13.130
involve me 'cause he was
always trying to protect me.

13:13.214 --> 13:14.756
They don't want
me to get involved.

13:14.839 --> 13:16.881
- But giving you a little
taste at the same time.

13:16.964 --> 13:19.339
- I guess so, yeah, yeah.

13:19.422 --> 13:22.464
♪ ♪

13:22.547 --> 13:24.214
Uncle Jerry was
a middle-aged guy.

13:24.297 --> 13:28.255
Just normal, average height,
normal, average build.

13:28.339 --> 13:31.089
But size doesn't matter.
Like my dad always used to say

13:31.172 --> 13:33.756
and still does say,
"As long as this works,

13:33.839 --> 13:35.964
that's all I need.
One finger."

13:36.047 --> 13:37.214
And it's the truth.

13:37.297 --> 13:38.923
- And the family
that's backing you.

13:39.005 --> 13:40.714
- Yeah, and a family
that's backing you.

13:40.798 --> 13:42.422
That's a big thing.

13:43.714 --> 13:46.130
♪ ♪

13:46.214 --> 13:47.964
Jerome was
getting the tickets,

13:48.047 --> 13:50.339
but when it came to...uh..
- Dispersing.

13:50.422 --> 13:53.047
- Dispersing the tickets,
I don't think he had

13:53.130 --> 13:56.422
the resources to do the big

13:56.506 --> 13:58.297
$1 million hits everywhere,

13:58.381 --> 14:00.172
so I think that's
where my brother

14:00.255 --> 14:02.172
took the reins of everything.

14:02.255 --> 14:05.130
So Uncle Jerry was getting

14:05.214 --> 14:07.923
the tickets
and selling them to my brother

14:08.005 --> 14:10.673
and then my brother would
sell them to other people

14:10.756 --> 14:15.589
and it was just a--literally,
it was a monopoly of scams.

14:19.005 --> 14:21.422
Every ticket was
a little different.

14:21.506 --> 14:23.214
The agreement
with Uncle Jerry

14:23.297 --> 14:25.506
was depending on the value
of the ticket.

14:25.589 --> 14:27.673
The $1 million tickets
were going for 50 grand.

14:27.756 --> 14:30.506
Uncle Jerry would get the 50,

14:30.589 --> 14:34.339
and then my brother would
get half of whoever won.

14:34.422 --> 14:36.839
And so, if they got
the payments for 20 years

14:36.923 --> 14:38.422
and so forth, he'd get half,

14:38.506 --> 14:40.172
and then the winner
would get half.

14:40.255 --> 14:42.339
So it was a better deal
for my brother, long-term,

14:42.422 --> 14:45.172
than it was for Uncle Jerry.

14:45.255 --> 14:48.214
[light music]

14:48.297 --> 14:53.130
♪ ♪

14:53.214 --> 14:55.130
I really didn't
think much of it,

14:55.214 --> 14:58.631
'cause someone
had to win, so...

14:58.714 --> 15:00.589
In my brother's eyes,
it was, "Okay, well,

15:00.673 --> 15:03.339
"instead of Joe Shmoe winning,
I'm gonna make,

15:03.422 --> 15:05.464
you know, John Shmoe win."

15:05.547 --> 15:06.923
The money's still
gonna go somewhere,

15:07.005 --> 15:09.255
you know, were just
redirecting it.

15:10.506 --> 15:12.047
The $1 million ticket

15:12.130 --> 15:13.714
was supposed to be
our wedding gift.

15:13.798 --> 15:16.673
We were married
November 24, 1997.

15:16.756 --> 15:18.214
- 1996.

15:18.297 --> 15:19.714
- 1996...

15:19.798 --> 15:21.464
let's start that over again.

15:21.547 --> 15:22.756
[laughter]

15:22.839 --> 15:24.172
Cut that.

15:24.255 --> 15:25.589
Whoops, I'm getting
my ass kicked tonight.

15:25.673 --> 15:27.923
[laughter]
Okay.

15:28.005 --> 15:30.881
Um, but that was gonna
be our gift, our wedding gift.

15:30.964 --> 15:33.673
Free of charge.
We didn't have to buy it.

15:35.881 --> 15:38.589
- The McDonald's piece
was in one of the little,

15:38.673 --> 15:40.255
I guess you'd call them eggs,

15:40.339 --> 15:42.214
like your kids get toys in
at the gumball machines.

15:42.297 --> 15:44.673
It was in there,
in the back of the freezer,

15:44.756 --> 15:46.714
underneath two ice cube trays.

15:47.631 --> 15:49.339
I remember exactly how it sat.

15:49.422 --> 15:50.464
- It was just chilling.

15:50.547 --> 15:52.631
- It was just chilling.

15:54.297 --> 15:55.714
- I always looked up
to my brother.

15:55.798 --> 15:58.756
He was my protector,
pretty much.

15:58.839 --> 16:00.589
He would always come
to visit me and throw me

16:00.673 --> 16:03.756
a couple thousand dollars,
like it was me giving away

16:03.839 --> 16:05.881
a couple dollars to the kids.

16:06.005 --> 16:10.172
This is our son Frankie.
He dropped about $150,000

16:10.255 --> 16:11.964
and we just decided
to take a picture,

16:12.047 --> 16:13.506
we kind of--thought
it was kind of funny.

16:13.589 --> 16:15.422
- I was so upset
over that picture.

16:15.506 --> 16:16.714
Because it was such dirty money

16:16.798 --> 16:18.964
around such a clean,
perfect baby.

16:19.047 --> 16:20.381
- Ah, it was pretty crazy,

16:20.464 --> 16:24.172
but...with that comes a price.

